#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:183
msgid "New Features"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:186
msgid "Integrated squared error (ISE) estimator added to ``histogram``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:187
msgid ""
"This method (``bins='stone'``) for optimizing the bin number is a "
"generalization of the Scott's rule. The Scott's rule assumes the "
"distribution is approximately Normal, while the ISE_ is a non-parametric "
"method based on cross-validation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:195
msgid "``max_rows`` keyword added for ``np.loadtxt``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:196
msgid ""
"New keyword ``max_rows`` in `numpy.loadtxt` sets the maximum rows of the "
"content to be read after ``skiprows``, as in `numpy.genfromtxt`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:200
msgid "modulus operator support added for ``np.timedelta64`` operands"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:201
msgid ""
"The modulus (remainder) operator is now supported for two operands of type "
"``np.timedelta64``. The operands may have different units and the return "
"value will match the type of the operands."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:207
msgid "Improvements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:210
msgid "no-copy pickling of numpy arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:211
msgid ""
"Up to protocol 4, numpy array pickling created 2 spurious copies of the data "
"being serialized.  With pickle protocol 5, and the ``PickleBuffer`` API, a "
"large variety of numpy arrays can now be serialized without any copy using "
"out-of-band buffers, and with one less copy using in-band buffers. This "
"results, for large arrays, in an up to 66% drop in peak memory usage."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:218
msgid "build shell independence"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:219
msgid ""
"NumPy builds should no longer interact with the host machine shell directly. "
"``exec_command`` has been replaced with ``subprocess.check_output`` where "
"appropriate."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:224
msgid "`np.polynomial.Polynomial` classes render in LaTeX in Jupyter notebooks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:225
msgid ""
"When used in a front-end that supports it, `Polynomial` instances are now "
"rendered through LaTeX. The current format is experimental, and is subject "
"to change."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:230
msgid "``randint`` and ``choice`` now work on empty distributions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:231
msgid ""
"Even when no elements needed to be drawn, ``np.random.randint`` and ``np."
"random.choice`` raised an error when the arguments described an empty "
"distribution. This has been fixed so that e.g. ``np.random.choice([], 0) == "
"np.array([], dtype=float64)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:237
msgid ""
"``linalg.lstsq``, ``linalg.qr``, and ``linalg.svd`` now work with empty "
"arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:238
msgid ""
"Previously, a ``LinAlgError`` would be raised when an empty matrix/empty "
"matrices (with zero rows and/or columns) is/are passed in. Now outputs of "
"appropriate shapes are returned."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:243
msgid ""
"Chain exceptions to give better error messages for invalid PEP3118 format "
"strings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:244
msgid "This should help track down problems."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:247
msgid "Einsum optimization path updates and efficiency improvements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:248
msgid "Einsum was synchronized with the current upstream work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:251
msgid ""
"`numpy.angle` and `numpy.expand_dims` now work on ``ndarray`` subclasses"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:252
msgid "In particular, they now work for masked arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:255
msgid "``NPY_NO_DEPRECATED_API`` compiler warning suppression"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:256
msgid ""
"Setting ``NPY_NO_DEPRECATED_API`` to a value of 0 will suppress the current "
"compiler warnings when the deprecated numpy API is used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:260
msgid "``np.diff`` Added kwargs prepend and append"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:261
msgid ""
"New kwargs ``prepend`` and ``append``, allow for values to be inserted on "
"either end of the differences.  Similar to options for `ediff1d`. Now the "
"inverse of `cumsum` can be obtained easily via ``prepend=0``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:266
msgid "ARM support updated"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:267
msgid ""
"Support for ARM CPUs has been updated to accommodate 32 and 64 bit targets, "
"and also big and little endian byte ordering. AARCH32 memory alignment "
"issues have been addressed. CI testing has been expanded to include AARCH64 "
"targets via the services of shippable.com."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:273
msgid "Appending to build flags"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:274
msgid ""
"``numpy.distutils`` has always overridden rather than appended to `LDFLAGS` "
"and other similar such environment variables for compiling Fortran "
"extensions. Now, if the `NPY_DISTUTILS_APPEND_FLAGS` environment variable is "
"set to 1, the behavior will be appending.  This applied to: `LDFLAGS`, "
"`F77FLAGS`, `F90FLAGS`, `FREEFLAGS`, `FOPT`, `FDEBUG`, and `FFLAGS`.  See "
"gh-11525 for more details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:282
msgid "Generalized ufunc signatures now allow fixed-size dimensions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:283
msgid ""
"By using a numerical value in the signature of a generalized ufunc, one can "
"indicate that the given function requires input or output to have dimensions "
"with the given size. E.g., the signature of a function that converts a polar "
"angle to a two-dimensional cartesian unit vector would be ``()->(2)``; that "
"for one that converts two spherical angles to a three-dimensional unit "
"vector would be ``(),()->(3)``; and that for the cross product of two three-"
"dimensional vectors would be ``(3),(3)->(3)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:291
msgid ""
"Note that to the elementary function these dimensions are not treated any "
"differently from variable ones indicated with a name starting with a letter; "
"the loop still is passed the corresponding size, but it can now count on "
"that size being equal to the fixed one given in the signature."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:297
msgid "Generalized ufunc signatures now allow flexible dimensions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:298
msgid ""
"Some functions, in particular numpy's implementation of ``@`` as ``matmul``, "
"are very similar to generalized ufuncs in that they operate over core "
"dimensions, but one could not present them as such because they were able to "
"deal with inputs in which a dimension is missing. To support this, it is now "
"allowed to postfix a dimension name with a question mark to indicate that "
"the dimension does not necessarily have to be present."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:305
msgid ""
"With this addition, the signature for ``matmul`` can be expressed as ``(m?,"
"n),(n,p?)->(m?,p?)``.  This indicates that if, e.g., the second operand has "
"only one dimension, for the purposes of the elementary function it will be "
"treated as if that input has core shape ``(n, 1)``, and the output has the "
"corresponding core shape of ``(m, 1)``. The actual output array, however, "
"has the flexible dimension removed, i.e., it will have shape ``(..., m)``. "
"Similarly, if both arguments have only a single dimension, the inputs will "
"be presented as having shapes ``(1, n)`` and ``(n, 1)`` to the elementary "
"function, and the output as ``(1, 1)``, while the actual output array "
"returned will have shape ``()``. In this way, the signature allows one to "
"use a single elementary function for four related but different signatures, "
"``(m,n),(n,p)->(m,p)``, ``(n),(n,p)->(p)``, ``(m,n),(n)->(m)`` and ``(n),(n)-"
">()``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:320
msgid "``np.clip`` and the ``clip`` method check for memory overlap"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:321
msgid ""
"The ``out`` argument to these functions is now always tested for memory "
"overlap to avoid corrupted results when memory overlap occurs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:325
msgid "New value ``unscaled`` for option ``cov`` in ``np.polyfit``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:326
msgid ""
"A further possible value has been added to the ``cov`` parameter of the ``np."
"polyfit`` function. With ``cov='unscaled'`` the scaling of the covariance "
"matrix is disabled completely (similar to setting ``absolute_sigma=True`` in "
"``scipy.optimize.curve_fit``). This would be useful in occasions, where the "
"weights are given by 1/sigma with sigma being the (known) standard errors of "
"(Gaussian distributed) data points, in which case the unscaled matrix is "
"already a correct estimate for the covariance matrix."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:335
msgid "Detailed docstrings for scalar numeric types"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:336
msgid ""
"The ``help`` function, when applied to numeric types such as `numpy.intc`, "
"`numpy.int_`, and `numpy.longlong`, now lists all of the aliased names for "
"that type, distinguishing between platform -dependent and -independent "
"aliases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:341
msgid "``__module__`` attribute now points to public modules"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:342
msgid ""
"The ``__module__`` attribute on most NumPy functions has been updated to "
"refer to the preferred public module from which to access a function, rather "
"than the module in which the function happens to be defined. This produces "
"more informative displays for functions in tools such as IPython, e.g., "
"instead of ``<function 'numpy.core.fromnumeric.sum'>`` you now see "
"``<function 'numpy.sum'>``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:350
msgid "Large allocations marked as suitable for transparent hugepages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:351
msgid ""
"On systems that support transparent hugepages over the madvise system call "
"numpy now marks that large memory allocations can be backed by hugepages "
"which reduces page fault overhead and can in some fault heavy cases improve "
"performance significantly. On Linux the setting for huge pages to be used, `/"
"sys/kernel/mm/transparent_hugepage/enabled`, must be at least `madvise`. "
"Systems which already have it set to `always` will not see much difference "
"as the kernel will automatically use huge pages where appropriate."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:359
msgid ""
"Users of very old Linux kernels (~3.x and older) should make sure that `/sys/"
"kernel/mm/transparent_hugepage/defrag` is not set to `always` to avoid "
"performance problems due concurrency issues in the memory defragmentation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:364
msgid "Alpine Linux (and other musl c library distros) support"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:365
msgid ""
"We now default to use `fenv.h` for floating point status error reporting. "
"Previously we had a broken default that sometimes would not report "
"underflow, overflow, and invalid floating point operations. Now we can "
"support non-glibc distributions like Alpine Linux as long as they ship `fenv."
"h`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:371
msgid "Speedup ``np.block`` for large arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:372
msgid ""
"Large arrays (greater than ``512 * 512``) now use a blocking algorithm based "
"on copying the data directly into the appropriate slice of the resulting "
"array. This results in significant speedups for these large arrays, "
"particularly for arrays being blocked along more than 2 dimensions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:378
msgid "``arr.ctypes.data_as(...)`` holds a reference to arr"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:379
msgid ""
"Previously the caller was responsible for keeping the array alive for the "
"lifetime of the pointer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:383
msgid "Speedup ``np.take`` for read-only arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:384
msgid ""
"The implementation of ``np.take`` no longer makes an unnecessary copy of the "
"source array when its ``writeable`` flag is set to ``False``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:388
msgid "Support path-like objects for more functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:389
msgid ""
"The ``np.core.records.fromfile`` function now supports ``pathlib.Path`` and "
"other path-like objects in addition to a file object. Furthermore, the ``np."
"load`` function now also supports path-like objects when using memory "
"mapping (``mmap_mode`` keyword argument)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:395
msgid "Better behaviour of ufunc identities during reductions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:396
msgid ""
"Universal functions have an ``.identity`` which is used when ``.reduce`` is "
"called on an empty axis."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:399
msgid ""
"As of this release, the logical binary ufuncs, `logical_and`, `logical_or`, "
"and `logical_xor`, now have ``identity`` s of type `bool`, where previously "
"they were of type `int`. This restores the 1.14 behavior of getting ``bool`` "
"s when reducing empty object arrays with these ufuncs, while also keeping "
"the 1.15 behavior of getting ``int`` s when reducing empty object arrays "
"with arithmetic ufuncs like ``add`` and ``multiply``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:406
msgid ""
"Additionally, `logaddexp` now has an identity of ``-inf``, allowing it to be "
"called on empty sequences, where previously it could not be."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:409
msgid ""
"This is possible thanks to the new :c:func:"
"`PyUFunc_FromFuncAndDataAndSignatureAndIdentity`, which allows arbitrary "
"values to be used as identities now."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:414
msgid "Improved conversion from ctypes objects"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:415
msgid ""
"Numpy has always supported taking a value or type from ``ctypes`` and "
"converting it into an array or dtype, but only behaved correctly for simpler "
"types. As of this release, this caveat is lifted - now:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:419
msgid ""
"The ``_pack_`` attribute of ``ctypes.Structure``, used to emulate C's "
"``__attribute__((packed))``, is respected."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:421
msgid "Endianness of all ctypes objects is preserved"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:422
msgid "``ctypes.Union`` is supported"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:423
msgid ""
"Non-representable constructs raise exceptions, rather than producing "
"dangerously incorrect results:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:426
msgid "Bitfields are no longer interpreted as sub-arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:427
msgid "Pointers are no longer replaced with the type that they point to"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:430
msgid "A new ``ndpointer.contents`` member"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:431
msgid ""
"This matches the ``.contents`` member of normal ctypes arrays, and can be "
"used to construct an ``np.array`` around the pointers contents.  This "
"replaces ``np.array(some_nd_pointer)``, which stopped working in 1.15.  As a "
"side effect of this change, ``ndpointer`` now supports dtypes with "
"overlapping fields and padding."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:438
msgid "``matmul`` is now a ``ufunc``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:439
msgid ""
"`numpy.matmul` is now a ufunc which means that both the function and the "
"``__matmul__`` operator can now be overridden by ``__array_ufunc__``. Its "
"implementation has also changed. It uses the same BLAS routines as `numpy."
"dot`, ensuring its performance is similar for large matrices."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:445
msgid "Start and stop arrays for ``linspace``, ``logspace`` and ``geomspace``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:446
msgid ""
"These functions used to be limited to scalar stop and start values, but can "
"now take arrays, which will be properly broadcast and result in an output "
"which has one axis prepended.  This can be used, e.g., to obtain linearly "
"interpolated points between sets of points."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:452
msgid "CI extended with additional services"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:453
msgid ""
"We now use additional free CI services, thanks to the companies that provide:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:455
msgid "Codecoverage testing via codecov.io"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:456
msgid "Arm testing via shippable.com"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:457
msgid "Additional test runs on azure pipelines"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:459
msgid ""
"These are in addition to our continued use of travis, appveyor (for wheels) "
"and LGTM"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:464
msgid "Changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:467
msgid "Comparison ufuncs will now error rather than return NotImplemented"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:468
msgid ""
"Previously, comparison ufuncs such as ``np.equal`` would return "
"`NotImplemented` if their arguments had structured dtypes, to help "
"comparison operators such as ``__eq__`` deal with those.  This is no longer "
"needed, as the relevant logic has moved to the comparison operators proper "
"(which thus do continue to return `NotImplemented` as needed). Hence, like "
"all other ufuncs, the comparison ufuncs will now error on structured dtypes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:476
msgid "Positive will now raise a deprecation warning for non-numerical arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:477
msgid ""
"Previously, ``+array`` unconditionally returned a copy. Now, it will raise a "
"``DeprecationWarning`` if the array is not numerical (i.e., if ``np."
"positive(array)`` raises a ``TypeError``. For ``ndarray`` subclasses that "
"override the default ``__array_ufunc__`` implementation, the ``TypeError`` "
"is passed on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:484
msgid "``NDArrayOperatorsMixin`` now implements matrix multiplication"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:485
msgid ""
"Previously, ``np.lib.mixins.NDArrayOperatorsMixin`` did not implement the "
"special methods for Python's matrix multiplication operator (``@``). This "
"has changed now that ``matmul`` is a ufunc and can be overridden using "
"``__array_ufunc__``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:491
msgid "The scaling of the covariance matrix in ``np.polyfit`` is different"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:492
msgid ""
"So far, ``np.polyfit`` used a non-standard factor in the scaling of the the "
"covariance matrix. Namely, rather than using the standard ``chisq/(M-N)``, "
"it scaled it with ``chisq/(M-N-2)`` where M is the number of data points and "
"N is the number of parameters.  This scaling is inconsistent with other "
"fitting programs such as e.g. ``scipy.optimize.curve_fit`` and was changed "
"to ``chisq/(M-N)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:499
msgid "``maximum`` and ``minimum`` no longer emit warnings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:500
msgid ""
"As part of code introduced in 1.10,  ``float32`` and ``float64`` set invalid "
"float status when a Nan is encountered in `numpy.maximum` and `numpy."
"minimum`, when using SSE2 semantics. This caused a `RuntimeWarning` to "
"sometimes be emitted. In 1.15 we fixed the inconsistencies which caused the "
"warnings to become more conspicuous. Now no warnings will be emitted."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:507
msgid "Umath and multiarray c-extension modules merged into a single module"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:508
msgid ""
"The two modules were merged, according to `NEP 15`_. Previously `np.core."
"umath` and `np.core.multiarray` were separate c-extension modules. They are "
"now python wrappers to the single `np.core/_multiarray_math` c-extension "
"module."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:515
msgid "``getfield`` validity checks extended"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:516
msgid ""
"`numpy.ndarray.getfield` now checks the dtype and offset arguments to "
"prevent accessing invalid memory locations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:520
msgid "NumPy functions now support overrides with ``__array_function__``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:521
msgid ""
"NumPy has a new experimental mechanism for overriding the implementation of "
"almost all NumPy functions on non-NumPy arrays by defining an "
"``__array_function__`` method, as described in `NEP 18`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:525
msgid ""
"This feature is not yet been enabled by default, but has been released to "
"facilitate experimentation by potential users. See the NEP for details on "
"setting the appropriate environment variable. We expect the NumPy 1.17 "
"release will enable overrides by default, which will also be more performant "
"due to a new implementation written in C."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:534
msgid "Arrays based off readonly buffers cannot be set ``writeable``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.16.0-notes.rst:535
msgid ""
"We now disallow setting the ``writeable`` flag True on arrays created from "
"``fromstring(readonly-buffer)``."
msgstr ""
